\f0\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 You asked about Pop-Mix earlier in our conversation, and at that point I had to flag that I couldn't find the term in the H0DN paper text \'97 it's not in the Figure 1 caption text I have access to, but you've confirmed it appears as a label 
\f1\i on
\f0\i0  the figure itself (likely on a pathway in the diagram). At the time I gave you a best-inference interpretation centered on Riess+24's combined Pop-I + Pop-II analysis. Now that we've worked through the full H0DN landscape \'97 Pop-I, Pop-II, all the anchors, all the routes \'97 I can give you a much sharper picture of what Pop-Mix means structurally and why it's a meaningful entry on the figure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 What "Pop-Mix" structurally must be\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Given the figure's organization (anchors 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  calibrators 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  SN Ia 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  Hubble flow), and given that Pop-I and Pop-II are explicitly labeled as separate calibrator routes, "Pop-Mix" is a route where 
\f2\b the same SN Ia hosts have distances measured by both Pop-I and Pop-II calibrators
\f0\b0  \'97 i.e., where Cepheids and TRGB (and possibly JAGB and Mira) are 
\f1\i all
\f0\i0  measured in the same set of host galaxies, with their distances combined into a single multi-method calibration.\
This is structurally different from any of the other routes on the figure:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pop-I (SH0ES)
\f0\b0 : Cepheids only as rung-2 calibrators\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pop-II (CCHP)
\f0\b0 : TRGB only as rung-2 calibrators\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pop-II via SBF
\f0\b0 : TRGB only, with SBF as rung-3\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pop-Mix
\f0\b0 : Cepheids 
\f1\i and
\f0\i0  TRGB (and JAGB) jointly calibrating the same SN Ia hosts\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The conceptual move is to treat the multiple calibrators not as competing measurements (which is the SH0ES vs CCHP framing) but as 
\f2\b complementary measurements of the same host distances
\f0\b0 . Each host has multiple independent rung-2 distances; you take a weighted average per host, then propagate to SN Ia calibration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 Why this is the right thing to do, in principle\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Pop-I/Pop-II split has been the structuring debate of the H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  field for ~10 years. Each side argues their methodology is more robust; each side argues the other has hidden systematics. The H0DN paper's deeper move \'97 and Pop-Mix is one expression of it \'97 is to ask: 
\f2\b why are we treating these as competing claims when they share the same SN Ia hosts and the same overall ladder structure?
\f0\b0 \
If Cepheids in NGC 1559 give \uc0\u956  = 31.40 and TRGB in NGC 1559 gives \u956  = 31.41, the right answer is 
\f1\i not
\f0\i0  "Cepheids say H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 73 and TRGB says H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 70, who's right?" The right answer is "NGC 1559 is at \uc0\u956  = 31.405 with smaller error bars than either method alone, and the SN Ia in NGC 1559 should be calibrated to that joint distance."\
Pop-Mix operationalizes this. By using 
\f1\i both
\f0\i0  calibrators per host, you:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Reduce per-host distance uncertainty
\f0\b0  (statistical advantage from combining)\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Identify per-host outliers
\f0\b0  where Pop-I and Pop-II disagree by more than expected (systematic flag)\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Average down population-specific systematics
\f0\b0  (Pop-I's crowding bias and Pop-II's metallicity sensitivity partially cancel if independently estimated)\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Get a more representative calibrator set
\f0\b0  (Cepheid hosts skew to late-type spirals; TRGB can reach E/S0; combined samples are more diverse)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 The canonical Pop-Mix measurement: Riess et al. 2024\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The most direct literature instance of this approach is 
\f2\b Riess et al. 2024
\f0\b0 , "JWST Validates HST Distance Measurements" (ApJ 977, 120). The paper's headline result is the JWST validation of HST Cepheid photometry, but the deeper contribution is a multi-method combined analysis using Cepheid + TRGB + JAGB distances to the same set of SN Ia hosts.\
The structure:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 5 SN Ia host galaxies
\f0\b0  observed with JWST NIRCam at multi-method depth: NGC 1559, NGC 4258, NGC 5468, NGC 5584, NGC 5643.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Three independent rung-2 measurements per host
\f0\b0 : Cepheids (Pop-I), TRGB (Pop-II), and JAGB (Pop-II).\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 One geometric anchor
\f0\b0 : NGC 4258 maser distance.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Per-host distance combination
\f0\b0 : each host's distance is the weighted average of the three calibrators.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
